@virginiayung and I want a syntax and mechanism for `rio color` to apply given operations only to selected channels. For comparison, ImageMagick’s `convert` works like this:

`convert input.tif -channel G -gamma 1.5 -channel B -gamma 0.5 -sigmoidal-contrast 3,50% -channel RGB output.tif`

Which is something like this in pseudocode:

```
G = gamma(G, 1.5);
B = gamma(B, 0.5);
B = sigmoid(B, 3, 50);
write([R, G, B], output.tif);
```

Implicitly, R is passed through. It amounts to a simple system for creating blocks of operations.

I don’t love the `convert` syntax (for example, it’s easy to forget to switch back to RGB at the end) but it seems to mostly work. I wonder about something maybe more like this:

`rio color 'G(gamma 1.6) B(gamma 0.5, sigmoid 3 50)' input.tif output.tif`

Or maybe full s-expressions, or…?

Right now all the bit logic is hardcoded into the message packing code.  It should be defined by yaml.

<!---
@huboard:{"order":2.625}
-->

Hi,

We encountered the following situation: while connecting to IPv6 peer, we mistakenly used IPv6 address as our local router id.
This caused the BGP handshake packet to be corrupt: since IPv6 address is 16 bytes and IPv4 is 4 bytes, the 12 bytes immediately after the router id came out corrupted.
This caused a subtle bug where Juniper router (in our case) complained that it received unknown capabilities.
We suggest to add validation to router id field, or throw an exception with clear message, or hash any router id to 4 bytes string.

Thanks, Yuriy.

P.S. Example of wrong configuration:
group defenseflow  {
… 
  neighbor 20.20.20.20 {
    description "20.20.20.20";
    router-id 2001:5:5::7;
    local-address 2001:5:5::7;
    local-as 150;
    peer-as 150;
    hold-time 180;
  }
}

